Hi JC,
The Bolts and bushings that hold the tops and bottoms of the shocks in place.
There are a couple of rubber bushings and a cupped washer that sandwich the
top of the shock tower to the  shock stud on the top of the shock and a rubber
bushing with a metal bushing inside that on the bottom on the front of the
bus. On the rear of the bus, as I recall, you have the same setup as on the
bottom of the front shocks on both the top and bottom of the rear. Everything
should be snug tight. If the rattling continues to happen look for evidence of
cracks around these anchor points.

The 73 bus that I had was very uncomfortable for my size on long trips. I had
difficulty getting my long legs around the steering column and the seat would
not go back far enough for my Daddy Long Legs.  Loved the T-4 motor and trans
loathed the carbs. If  the diaphram in the brake booster goes, get it replaces
ASAP as you will pay the price for it in your knees for years thereafter. No
Kidding. Procrastinate and you'll be using a cane or a walker. By the way 2
walkers with a  pinned 2x4 bridge on each end and a 2X12 plank make a pretty
good light folding adjustable scaffold around the house and job site. The
bridge must be pinned in place with a nail in a small hole to keep the 2x4
bridge from sliding off the handles.

LUV
Unka Dave



